04465nam a22005175i 9780226292854DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226292854  a(DE-B1597)523414  a(OCoLC)994600286  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aSB945.C8G54 2011 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a338.1/73510975a338.1735109751 aGiesen, James C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBoll Weevil Blues :bCotton, Myth, and Power in the American South /cJames C. Giesen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2012] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b5 halftones, 4 maps, 10 figures, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Myth Making on the Cotton Frontier -- t2. Cultures of Resistance in Texas and Louisiana: Tenants Make Sense of the Boll Weevil -- t3. “Map Maker, Troublemaker, History Maker”: The Boll Weevil Threatens the Delta -- t4. Delta Solutions Big and Small -- t5. “The Herald of Prosperity”: The Promise of Diversification in Alabama -- t6. “You Will Be Poor and Ignorant and Your Children Will Be the Same”: The Boll Weevil Myth Transformed -- t7. Cotton’s Obituaries: The Boll Weevil in Georgia -- tConclusion: The Boll Weevil’s Lost Revolution -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween the 1890s and the early 1920s, the boll weevil slowly ate its way across the Cotton South from Texas to the Atlantic Ocean. At the turn of the century, some Texas counties were reporting crop losses of over 70 percent, as were areas of Louisiana, Arkansas, and Mississippi. By the time the boll weevil reached the limits of the cotton belt, it had destroyed much of the region’s chief cash crop—tens of billions of pounds of cotton, worth nearly a trillion dollars. As staggering as these numbers may seem, James C. Giesen demonstrates that it was the very idea of the boll weevil and the struggle over its meanings that most profoundly changed the South—as different groups, from policymakers to blues singers, projected onto this natural disaster the consequences they feared and the outcomes they sought. Giesen asks how the myth of the boll weevil’s lasting impact helped obscure the real problems of the region—those caused not by insects, but by landowning patterns, antiquated credit systems, white supremacist ideology, and declining soil fertility. Boll Weevil Blues brings together these cultural, environmental, and agricultural narratives in a novel and important way that allows us to reconsider the making of the modern American South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBoll weevilxEconomic aspectszSouthern States. 0aCottonxEconomic aspectszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aagriculture industry, crop science, texas, alabama, georgia, mississippi, policymakers, blues music, singers, natural disasters, landowning patterns, antiquated credit systems, white supremacist ideology, soil fertility, agricultural narrative, environmental narratives, modern american south, cotton farming, textiles, southern united states, economic conditions, 20th century, insects, louisiana, tenant farms, boll weevil myth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022629287840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226292854423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226292854/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles